job_description: DATA ANALYST - job post University of Washington 1,370 reviews 1400 NE Campus Parkway, Seattle, WA 98195 $4,554 - $7,920 a month -  Full-time You must create an Indeed account before continuing to the company website to apply Apply on company site save-icon Job details Salary $4,554 - $7,920 a month Job Type Full-time Benefits: As a UW employee, you will enjoy generous benefits and work/life programs. For a complete description of our benefits for this position, please visit our website, click here. As a UW employee, you have a unique opportunity to change lives on our campuses, in our state and around the world. UW employees offer their boundless energy, creative problem solving skills and dedication to build stronger minds and a healthier world. UW faculty and staff also enjoy outstanding benefits, professional growth opportunities and unique resources in an environment noted for diversity, intellectual excitement, artistic pursuits and natural beauty. The UW Division of Allergy and Infectious Diseases (DAID) has an outstanding opportunity for a full-time data manager & analyst. This position will support the Chu Lab in clinical and laboratory data analysis for several large-scale studies of the epidemiology and transmission of SARS-CoV-2 and other respiratory pathogens in the Seattle area. This position will involve analysis of clinical and biospecimen data from community-based and clinical-based enrollment of individuals with respiratory illness, and analysis of these data to characterize the epidemiology of pathogens causing respiratory symptoms in a variety of diverse settings, the transmission of pathogens within households, and the clinical characteristics of individuals presenting with these pathogens. This is a collaborative project, and will involve interfacing with partnering stakeholders, clinicians, bioinformaticians, and a variety of study personnel, including trainees The Research Data Manager/Analyst will need to develop a deep understanding of each source-data structure, and have the intellectual dexterity to provide data management support (extraction, integration, validation) while collaborating with persons in a variety of fields: clinical informatics, data science, and epidemiology. Ideal candidates should have had solid experience with healthcare data, and excellent programming skills with SQL. We are seeking someone who is excited about the opportunity of working in a fast -paced environment, and who has resourcefulness, independent problem solving, excellent time management skills, attention to detail and the ability to negotiate and communicate priorities. DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES Data Investigation and Analysis (70%): Works with study PI(s), fellows, epidemiologists, bioinformaticians and other research staff to develop innovative solutions to abstract and integrate data in support of studies with large-scale data. Consults with faculty, fellows, coordinators and research scientists to interpret objectives and identify data needs. Generates complex database queries and ad hoc reports to uncover clinical trends and insights. Validates final data product through coordination with investigator. Investigates and identifies data idiosyncrasies and fluctuations and makes recommendations that support goals and objectives. Work independently to analyze study data using SAS, Stata or other software and prepare data for manuscripts. Methods Development and Study Planning (15%): Work closely with investigators to understand project goals, then independently develop the format of the data required to address the goals. Consider feasibility and appropriate data collection tools to develop analysis plans that will translate collected data into results. Work with investigators to explain the statistical processes and analysis plans developed and collaborate to refine methodologies as required. Utilize fundamental theories and develop them for application to specific project needs. This requires a strong comprehension of biostatistical analyses and an ability to develop innovative interpretations and applications of existing practices. Communication of Findings (10%): Summarize and interpret results of analyses for investigators and staff, incorporating appropriate inference and multiplicity adjustments. Prepare tabular, graphical, and statistical reports for scientific papers and grants, following the formatting requirements of the journals (eg high resolution graphics). Assist in writing papers and review them for correctness and completeness. Attend relevant study meetings including: Weekly data meetings, lab meetings, clinical meetings. Data Quality (5%): Work closely with Data Managers, Research Coordinators, and other staff to ensure the accuracy and consistency of data. Resolve data discrepancies and database issues through coordination with clinical team. Implement and maintain Data QC protocols for clinical trials and other research projects and collaborate with study partners on Data QA/QC workflow efficacy. Advise on case report form development and on dataset preparation. MINIMUM REQUIREMENTS Bachelor’s Degree in Bioinformatics, Statistics or related field and two years experience. Equivalent education/experience will substitute for all minimum qualifications except when there are legal requirements, such as a license/certification/registration. ADDITIONAL REQUIREMENTS Experience with R, SAS, Tableau or STATA. Strong troubleshooting skills in working with complex server configurations. Ability to adhere to institutional review board (IRB) regulations related to studies of human subjects. Ability to work well cross functionally, especially with technical teams. Demonstrated ability to maintain strict confidentiality of medical and surveillance records. DESIRED QUALIFICATIONS Advanced training in computer or data science, programming or informatics. Education in data science, health services research, health policy. Experience with Tableau and REDCap. Experience with Epic or other electronic health records systems. Experience in healthcare or medical data management, and/or biomedical informatics. Application Process: The application process for UW positions may include completion of a variety of online assessments to obtain additional information that will be used in the evaluation process. These assessments may include Work Authorization, Cover Letter and/or others. Any assessments that you need to complete will appear on your screen as soon as you select “Apply to this position”. Once you begin an assessment, it must be completed at that time; if you do not complete the assessment you will be prompted to do so the next time you access your “My Jobs” page. If you select to take it later, it will appear on your "My Jobs" page to take when you are ready. Please note that your application will not be reviewed, and you will not be considered for this position until all required assessments have been completed. Committed to attracting and retaining a diverse staff, the University of Washington will honor your experiences, perspectives and unique identity. Together, our community strives to create and maintain working and learning environments that are inclusive, equitable and welcoming. The University of Washington is an affirmative action and equal opportunity employer. All qualified applicants will receive consideration for employment without regard to race, color, religion, sex, sexual orientation, gender identity, gender expression, national origin, age, protected veteran or disabled status, or genetic information. To request disability accommodation in the application process, contact the Disability Services Office at 206-543-6450 or dso@uw.edu. Applicants considered for this position will be required to disclose if they are the subject of any substantiated findings or current investigations related to sexual misconduct at their current employment and past employment. Disclosure is required under Washington state law. COVID-19 VACCINATION REQUIREMENT Employees of the University of Washington are required to be fully vaccinated against COVID-19 unless a medical or religious exemption is approved. Being fully vaccinated means that an individual is at least two weeks past their final dose of an authorized COVID-19 vaccine regimen. As a condition of employment, newly hired employees will be required to provide proof of their COVID-19 vaccination. View the Final candidate guide to COVID-19 vaccination requirement webpage for information about the medical or religious exemption process for final candidates.
